{"title_page": "Christian Ranucci", "text_new": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Christian Ranucci\n| image_size         =\n| image_name         = \n| image_caption      = \n| birth_name         = Christian Jean Gilbert Ranucci\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1954|4|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Avignon]], [[French Fourth Republic|France]]\n| cause              = Execution by [[guillotine]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1976|7|28|1954|4|6}}\n| death_place        = [[Baumettes prison]], [[Marseilles]], [[French Fifth Republic|France]]\n| resting_place      = Cimeti\u00e8re Saint-V\u00e9ran, Avignon<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/114167802 Christian Jean Ranucci (1954-1976)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110172907/https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/114167802 |date=2016-11-10 }} on [https://www.findagrave.com Find a Grave.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911163501/http://www.findagrave.com/ |date=2016-09-11 }}. Retrieved 10 November 2016.</ref>\n| height             = 5 ft 8 in\n| other_names        = \"Le bourreau du bois de Valdonne\" (\"The torturer of the wood of Valdonne\")<ref>J\u00e9r\u00f4me Ferracci, ''Le M\u00e9ridional'', June 1974; cited by [[Gilles Perrault]] (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 141.</ref>\n| occupation         = [[Door-to-door|Travelling salesman]]\n| conviction = [[Child abduction]] & [[Child murder|murder]] (March 10, 1976)\n| conviction_penalty = [[Capital punishment]] (March 10, 1976)\n| conviction_status  = Executed by guillotine on July 28, 1976\n| parents            = Jean Ranucci and H\u00e9lo\u00efse Mathon\n| victims            = Marie-Dolor\u00e8s Rambla, 8\n| weapons            = [[Rock (geology)|Stones]]<br>[[Switchblade|Flick knife]]\n| states             = [[Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne]]\n| locations          = [[Marseilles]] <small>(abduction)</small> <br/> [[Belcod\u00e8ne]] <small>([[Traffic collision|car accident]])</small> <br>[[Peypin]] <small>([[Crime scene|murder scene]])</small>\n| date               = June 3, 1974\n| apprehended   = June 5, 1974\n}}\n\n'''Christian Ranucci''' (April 6, 1954&nbsp;\u2013 July 28, 1976) was a travelling [[door-to-door]] salesman who abducted and killed an eight-year-old girl on [[Whit Monday]], 1974. For these crimes, he  was one of the last persons [[Capital punishment in France#Executions since 1959|executed in France]]. He was convicted of the abduction and murder on March 10, 1976.\n\nHis case greatly influenced the debate over [[capital punishment in France]] after the book ''Le Pull-over rouge'' (1978) was published by former lawyer and journalist [[Gilles Perrault]]. It called Ranucci's guilt into question, and had a notable impact on public opinion, having sold over one million copies.<ref name=\"50ansfaitsdivers\">[http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x16njet_reportage-50-ans-de-faits-divers-christian-ranucci_webcam ''50 ans de faits divers'', \"Christian Ranucci : la v\u00e9rit\u00e9 impossible\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407051919/http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x16njet_reportage-50-ans-de-faits-divers-christian-ranucci_webcam |date=2015-04-07 }}, [[13\u00e8me Rue (TV channel)|13<sup>e</sup> Rue]], July 13, 2006.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nChristian Ranucci was born in Avignon, France on April 6, 1954, to Jean Ranucci (1921&ndash;1988), a board painter and veteran of the [[First Indochina War|Indochina War]], and H\u00e9lo\u00efse Mathon (1922&ndash;2013), a [[caregiver]].\n\nWhen he was four years old, he witnessed his father slashing his mother in the face with a knife \u2014 similar to the one Ranucci would later use to commit murder<ref name=\"50ansfaitsdivers\" /> \u2014 at the door of a court after their divorce had been pronounced. However, other sources, like Ranucci's father, testified that his son did not really witness this attack, but only saw his injured mother as a [[nursemaid]] was bringing him in her arms back at home.<ref>[[Gilles Perrault]] (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 132.</ref>\n\nMother and son soon fled, moving home numerous times, as H\u00e9lo\u00efse Mathon was afraid that her ex-husband would kill them both (although Jean  never attempted to find his son). As a result of this experience, she became an overprotective mother. Years later, Ranucci, charged with Rambla's murder, confessed to the [[examining magistrate]] that he had lived his entire childhood with the constant fear that his father, depicted as violent by his mother, would eventually find and kill him.<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over-rouge'', Ramsay, p. 195.</ref>\n\nDuring his school years, Ranucci was described as a mediocre pupil, repeating a year, but still earning his [[National diploma (France)|National Diploma]] (BEPC) at the age of 17. He was often violent towards his schoolmates, and remained immature and uncommunicative as a young man.<ref name=\"nationalservicecomrade\">[http://www.justice-affairescriminelles.org/Dossierranucci/ARabineau2.html Dossier Ranucci: entretien avec Alain Rabineau - Dossier Ranucci : Peut-on douter ?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728030251/http://www.justice-affairescriminelles.org/Dossierranucci/ARabineau2.html |date=2014-07-28 }}</ref> Meanwhile, he worked as a waiter at a bar, Le Rio Bravo, owned by his mother, located in [[Saint-Jean-de-Moirans]], near [[Voiron]] ([[Is\u00e8re]]), which he ran when she was absent.<ref name=\"50ansfaitsdivers\" />\n\nThey had lived in [[Nice]] since 1970. Ranucci eventually went to [[Wittlich]], in [[Rhineland-Palatinate]] ([[West Germany]]), in order to complete his [[Military service#France|military service]], which ended in March 1974. According to testimony by several comrades from his army days, his behaviour was impulsive, and his reactions were sometimes disproportionate.<ref name=\"nationalservicecomrade\" /> Later, as the murder case against him was unfolding, he was picked out as the abductor and offender of two children from Nice, but this was not pursued, nor formally proven. On May 24, 1974, he was hired by Ets COTTO, a company that made and sold air-conditioning equipment based in Nice, and began working as a door-to-door salesman.<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 166.</ref>\n\n==The crime==\nWhen his mother refused to accompany him on a [[Pentecost]] weekend trip, Ranucci left Nice alone on June 2, 1974. After visiting the region, he arrived in Marseille on the morning of June 3, 1974. Looking for the home of a former military service comrade, he stopped in the Cit\u00e9 Sainte-Agn\u00e8s housing estate ([[4th arrondissement of Marseille|4th arrondissement]]). Distracted by the sight of a group of children involved in numerous games, he came across Marie-Dolor\u00e8s Rambla, eight years old, and her six-and-a-half year old brother Jean-Baptiste,  along with two nearby children playing behind a building, in the car park of a local garage.<ref>G\u00e9rard Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture. L'affaire Ranucci, toute la v\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur le pull-over rouge'', Pascal Petiot, pp. 157; 216-218.</ref>\n\nWhen the Rambla children were alone, around 11:10{{nbsp}}am - 11:15{{nbsp}}am, he moved his car to the car park, on the same level where  the children were. Telling them he had lost a \"big black dog\", he asked for their help in searching for it. Sending the little boy off to track down the non-existent dog, he stayed with Marie-Dolor\u00e8s, chatting for a few minutes, then persuaded her to get into his car - a grey Peugeot 304. According to his later confession, the girl was initially reluctant to go with him, making him repeat his offer; he eventually gained her trust by promising to return her home for lunch time.\n\nAfter being arrested, he was not recognized by the two witnesses to the abduction, and the only physical evidence implicating him in this phase of the crime was a drawing he made while in police custody showing the estate where the Rambla family lived.<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, pp. 116-121.</ref>\n\nAn hour later, arriving at a crossroads, he went through a stop sign and collided with another car, damaging both vehicles. He then turned around and fled in the direction of Marseilles, drove a few hundred metres before stopping at the bottom of a hill, exited from his car with the young girl, and climbed up into underbrush holding her left arm. Hearing Marie-Dolor\u00e8s screaming and crying (she had just lost her right shoe and had to walk barefoot over the vegetation),<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, p. 27.</ref> he grabbed her by the neck and pushed her temple to the ground. He hit her head with stones then stabbed her in the throat with his [[Switchblade|flick knife]] (she reportedly received about fifteen blows).<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, pp. 23; 110-112.</ref><ref name=\"Rambla_88-92\">Pierre Rambla (2008). ''Le \u2033Cirque\" Rouge ou Le mensonge m\u00e9diatique et l'argent du sang'', Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des \u00c9crivains, pp. 20; 88-92.</ref> Rambla tried to resist by raising her right hand, but Ranucci soon stabbed the dorsal side of her hand.<ref name=\"Rambla_88-92\" /> Afterwards, he covered the body with briars and thornbushes.\n\nReturning to his car, he drove for a while, then hid in a mushroom bed in order to change his flat tire, change his bloodied clothes, clean up, and hide his knife. However, when leaving, he needed help from people to get his car out of the mud. After having accepted a cup of tea, he got back to his home, Corniche Fleurie (overlooking Nice).<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, pp. 33-37.</ref>{{,}}<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, pp. 29-30.</ref>\n\n==Arrest, confession and profile==\nRanucci was arrested two days after the murder as he was returning from his office to his home in Nice. The girl's corpse had been found shortly before by a squad of [[National Gendarmerie|gendarmes]]. He had been identified by his registration plate number, provided by witnesses to the car accident during his flight with the child. He confessed to the abduction and murder of Marie-Dolor\u00e8s Rambla, and drew an accurate sketch of the kidnapping, then indicated the place where he disposed of the murder weapon, his bloodied flick knife, which was later found buried in a peat field stack by gendarmes.\n\nPsychiatrists who heard Ranucci's conversation during sessions diagnosed him as having an \"immature and backward sexuality\". According to their report this, coupled with a need for company, had led to the desire to take children and spend time with them. He was not [[Offender profiling|profiled]] as a  [[Pedophilia|pedophile]], but rather as someone whose sexual identity remained undefined, though the psychiatrists asserted he showed \"keen interest\" in children. While confessing, Ranucci claimed he had no intention of harming the girl and only wished to go for a ride with her.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jul/29/archive-guillotine-returns-france-1976 From the archive, 29 July 1976: \"Guillotine returns after two years\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415011544/https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jul/29/archive-guillotine-returns-france-1976 |date=15 April 2017 }}, [https://www.theguardian.com theguardian.com], July 29, 2011.</ref> He explained the murder was a result of panic and fear due to the accident.\n\nHis motive for the abduction still remains unclear, as no signs of rape or other sexual assault were found on the victim's body.\n\nMonths later, while incarcerated at [[Baumettes prison]] ([[9th arrondissement of Marseille]]), he repudiated his confession after learning he was of the same [[blood type]] as the little girl (bloodstains had been found on his pants seized in his car trunk),<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, p. 322.</ref> and hearing about a local pedophile who wore a red polo shirt or sweater \u2014 according to testimonies \u2014 similar to the one discovered near the mushroom bed where he had hidden after the murder.<ref name=\"Perraultp222-223\">G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 222-223.</ref>\n\nAndr\u00e9 Fraticelli, Ranucci's lawyer, originally planned to plead [[mitigating circumstances]], citing his client's difficult childhood, the sight of his father slashing his mother's face, and the numerous moves made across France as a defence in court. Fraticelli wanted the jury to consider Ranucci's [[wikt:state of mind|state of mind]] and consciousness while committing murder, and whether he was really accountable for the crime, rather than his guilt.{{efn|According to article 64 of the [[French Penal Code of 1810|Penal Code]], no one can be tried if he acted in a state of [[Criminal insanity|insanity]].<ref>[http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichCodeArticle.do?idArticle=LEGIARTI000006490631&cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006071029&dateTexte=19940228 Code p\u00e9nal (ancien) - Article 64] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221090225/https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichCodeArticle.do?idArticle=LEGIARTI000006490631&cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006071029&dateTexte=19940228 |date=2016-12-21 }}. Retrieved 10 December 2016.</ref>}}<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 244-246.</ref> However, as Ranucci had retracted his confession, his other two lawyers conformed to his wishes, and chose to plead his innocence.{{efn|Fraticelli said about the defence strategy: \"You do not play poker with a man's life (...). This is the reason why I thought we had to plead guilty, with mitigating circumstances which were densely represented and possible.\"}}<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 248.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H8HmoRp8QlI?t=48m30s |title=Christian Ranucci : l'\u00e9nigme du pull-over rouge - Faites entrer l'accus\u00e9 #FELA |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= July 17, 2003 |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=[[France 2]] |access-date=30 June 2015 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Trial and execution ==\nHe was tried in [[Aix-en-Provence]] in southern France on March 9 and 10, 1976, just three weeks after [[Patrick Henry (French murderer)|Patrick Henry]] was arrested in [[Troyes]] for another child murder. Journalists described [[public opinion]] as sensitive to the point of hysteria, demanding death penalties for child murderers.\n\nOn the advice of his mother, Ranucci came to [[Cour d'assises|court]] dressed like a clergyman, sporting a large [[pectoral cross]], which irritated most of the jury, and was interpreted by a few observers as an indication of his immaturity. Ranucci appeared arrogant during the trial, denying the crime and his guilt, despite the physical evidence and the details he had provided during his confession.<ref>[http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x79gec_l-affaire-ranucci-l-ombre-d-un-dout_news ''Secrets d'actualit\u00e9'', \"Affaire Ranucci : l'ombre d'un doute\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819084955/http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x79gec_l-affaire-ranucci-l-ombre-d-un-dout_news |date=2014-08-19 }}, [[M6 (TV channel)|M6]], September 4, 2005.</ref>{{,}}<ref>Genevi\u00e8ve Donadini (2016). ''Le proc\u00e8s Ranucci : T\u00e9moignage d'un jur\u00e9 d'assises'', L'Harmattan, p. 52.</ref> Found guilty on all counts on March 10, 1976, he was sentenced to death. During the last hearing, and after his advocate's plea, minutes were communicated at the last moment to the jury and the defence lawyers, which, while not unheard of or illegal, was an extremely rare procedure. This was later used as an argument before the [[Court of Cassation (France)|Court of Cassation]].\n\nAgain on his mother's advice, Ranucci wrote a 74-page document titled \"''R\u00e9capitulatif''\" (\"Summary\") while on [[death row]], in which he summed up the case from his point of view, and attempted to prove he was innocent. G\u00e9rard Bouladou, a retired police officer who has written books about the case, has observed signs of [[Pathological lying|mythomania]] in this document and argued that Ranucci was trying to persuade himself of his own innocence.<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, p. 229-230.</ref> His [[Court of  Cassation (France)#Appeals|appeal]] for a second trial was denied by the Court of Cassation on June 17, 1976.<ref>[http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichJuriJudi.do?oldAction=rechJuriJudi&idTexte=JURITEXT000007061353&fastReqId=919750374&fastPos=1/  \"Crim., 17 juin 1976, pourvoi n\u00b0 76-90888 (Rejet du pourvoi en cassation de Christian Ranucci)\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812115901/http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichJuriJudi.do?oldAction=rechJuriJudi&idTexte=JURITEXT000007061353&fastReqId=919750374&fastPos=1%2F |date=2014-08-12 }}.</ref>\n\nOn July 26, President [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]] eventually refused a pardon for Ranucci. He was executed by [[guillotine]] in the courtyard of [[Baumettes prison]], in Marseilles, on July 28, 1976, at 4:13{{nbsp}}am. Two of his lawyers who witnessed the execution claimed his last words were \"R\u00e9habilitez-moi!\" (\"Clear my name!\"), but executioner [[Andr\u00e9 Obrecht]] wrote in his memoirs that the condemned said nothing before dying, his last word being a \"Negative!\" shouted at the chaplain when he refused to receive communion. His third lawyer, Andr\u00e9 Fraticelli, confirmed that Ranucci never asked to be rehabilitated. It is also specified in the minutes of the execution that Ranucci \"made no statement\".<ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1976/07/29/le-proces-verbal-officiel_2951905_1819218.html?xtmc=ranucci&xtcr=149 \"LE PROC\u00c8S-VERBAL OFFICIEL\"], ''[[Le Monde]]'', July 29, 1976.</ref>\n\n== Aftermath: controversy, political debate and attempted requests for review ==\nA novel by [[Gilles Perrault]] entitled ''Le Pull-over rouge'' (''The Red Sweater''), disputed Ranucci's involvement in the crime, expressing the writer's doubts about his guilt. The title of the book refers to a red sweater found hidden in the mushroom bed where Ranucci hid after his car accident, which seemed similar to that worn by another man who [[child sexual abuse|sexually abused]] children in another Marseilles estate, just two days before Rambla's kidnapping and murder.<ref name=\"Perraultp222-223\" /> During the inquiry, when asked about the sweater, Ranucci denied being its owner. In his book, Perrault took on board Ranucci's final defence, arguing that a [[Brain concussion|concussion]] he allegedly suffered as a result of the accident, right at the bottom of the [[crime scene]], caused Ranucci to become victim to manipulation and impersonation by the \"real murderer\". In this theory, the man is supposed to have moved the unconscious door-to-door to the [[Car seat|rear seat]] of Ranucci's own car, then drove the vehicle (carrying Ranucci) to the mushroom bed where he then hid his red sweater.<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, pp. 387-395.</ref> However, nothing within the penal case could corroborate this version; Perrault himself had no explanation or rebuttal to the main evidence, in particular the hiding place of the murder weapon Ranucci revealed.\n\nThe victim's father, Pierre Rambla, vehemently opposed the book and the subsequent campaign that supported Perrault's theses, arguing it made his family suffer, especially his elder son Jean-Baptiste who is among the last people to have seen Marie-Dolor\u00e8s alive.<ref>P. Rambla (2008). ''Le \"Cirque\" Rouge'', Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des \u00c9crivains, pp. 26-29; 56-65.</ref>\n\nThe book was made into a film by [[Michel Drach]] in 1979, starring [[Serge Av\u00e9dikian]] as Ranucci.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/film/le-pull-over-rouge |title=Le Pull-Over Rouge |publisher=Time Out Digital Limited |accessdate=5 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915124210/http://www.timeout.com/london/film/le-pull-over-rouge |archivedate=15 September 2016 }}</ref> A television film about the case, ''L'affaire Christian Ranucci: Le combat d'une m\u00e8re'', starring Alexandre Hamidi and [[Catherine Frot]] as Christian Ranucci and his mother, was broadcast in 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lemonde.fr/vous/article/2010/01/16/l-affaire-ranucci-le-combat-d-une-mere_1292538_3238.html | title=L'affaire Christian Ranucci: Le combat d'une m\u00e8re | publisher=Le Monde.fr | date=January 16, 2010 | accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref>{{,}}<ref>{{cite Web|url=http://www.tf1international.com/int_fiche.php?Film=295 |title=A Mother's Combat - TF1 International |publisher=TF1 International.com |accessdate=2 April 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402082452/http://www.tf1international.com/int_fiche.php?Film=295 |archivedate=2 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe controversy next entered politics, influencing the [[Capital punishment in France#Abolition|debate on capital punishment in France]], which culminated in criminal lawyer, and newly nominated Minister of Justice, [[Robert Badinter]] addressing the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] in September 1981 to defend his bill to abolish capital punishment. As a request for reconsideration had been submitted to him, he claimed, with regard to the Ranucci case, that there were: \"too many questions about his case, and [that] these questions were sufficient [...] to condemn the death penalty\".<ref>[http://blog.bnf.fr/gallica/index.php/2013/04/29/discours-sur-labolition-de-la-peine-de-mort-mise-en-ligne-du-manuscrit-de-robert-badinter/ Discours de Robert Badinter sur l'abolition de la peine de mort] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812085152/http://blog.bnf.fr/gallica/index.php/2013/04/29/discours-sur-labolition-de-la-peine-de-mort-mise-en-ligne-du-manuscrit-de-robert-badinter/ |date=2014-08-12 }}, [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France#Digital library|Gallica]], September 17, 1981.</ref> On the other hand, some journalists who covered the case refuted Perrault's [[miscarriage of justice]] theory. Christian Chardon, who covered the case for ''[[Le Nouveau D\u00e9tective|D\u00e9tective]]'', wrote an article for the newspaper ''[[Minute (French newspaper)|Minute]]'' titled \"Non ! L'affaire Ranucci n'est pas une erreur judiciaire\" (\"No! The Ranucci case was not a miscarriage of justice\") in late 1978, in which he recapped the key points of the case and argued for Ranucci's guilt. Chardon denied that Ranucci had been tortured as claimed during his trial. (In particular, he had accused Commissioner G\u00e9rard Alessandra, chief of the criminal section \"Nord\" in the H\u00f4tel de Police de Marseille, who was in charge of the inquiry.)<ref>Christian Chardon (September 13, 1978). \"Non ! L'affaire Ranucci n'est pas une erreur judiciaire\", ''[[Minute (French newspaper)|Minute]]'' no 857, p. 27.</ref> In late 1979, Jean Laborde published an article in ''[[Paris-Match]]'' which he titled \"Ranucci innocent ? Eh bien non !\" (\"Ranucci innocent? Well no!\"), also refuting Perrault's theory of Ranucci's innocence.\n\nIn 1989, having accused the policemen in charge of the inquiry of \"abuse of authority\" in a 1985 TV program titled ''Qui a tu\u00e9 Christian Ranucci?'' (''Who killed Christian Ranucci?''), Gilles Perrault, as well as the presenter, was found guilty of defamation and fined 30,000 francs to be paid to each of the five policemen, a sentence confirmed and raised on appeals and ''cassation'' to 70,000 francs for each plaintiff.<ref>[https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichJuriJudi.do?idTexte=JURITEXT000007623311 Cour de cassation, Chambre criminelle, du 4 f\u00e9vrier 1992, 90-86.069, In\u00e9dit].</ref>{{,}}<ref name=\"50ansfaitsdivers\" /> In 2008, Perrault and his publisher [[Fayard]] were found guilty of defamation against the Marseille police in another book, ''L'ombre de Christian Ranucci'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fayard.fr/lombre-de-christian-ranucci-9782213628875 |title=L'ombre de Christian Ranucci |publisher=[[Fayard|\u00c9ditions Fayard]] |accessdate=5 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105210208/http://www.fayard.fr/lombre-de-christian-ranucci-9782213628875 |archivedate=5 January 2016 }}</ref> in which it was stated that the investigators behaved with \"casualness and partisanship\". Perrault was fined 5,000 [[euro]]s and his publisher an equal sum for each policeman defamed, a decision confirmed and increased to 10,000 euro for each of the four policemen on appeal in 2009.<ref>[http://www.laprovence.com/actu/gilles-perrault-et-son-editeur-condamnes-pour-diffamation \"Gilles Perrault et son \u00e9diteur condamn\u00e9s pour diffamation\"], ''[[La Provence]]'', January 27, 2009.</ref>\n\nSince the publishing of ''Le Pull-over rouge'', which was followed by the creation of the \"Comit\u00e9 national pour la r\u00e9vision du proc\u00e8s Ranucci\", there have been three requests for a review of the Ranucci trial, all being ultimately rejected, the Minister of Justice and afterwards the \"Commission de r\u00e9vision des condamnations p\u00e9nales\" of the Court of cassation arguing each time that no new facts had proven Ranucci's innocence nor even cast doubt upon his guilt.<ref>[[Associated Press]] (November 30, 1991). [https://www.lesoir.be/art/m/le-pull-over-rouge-pas-de-revision-du-proces-ranucci_t-19911130-Z04PPH.html \"'Le pull-over rouge': pas de r\u00e9vision du proc\u00e8s Ranucci\"], ''[[Le Soir]]''</ref>{{,}}<ref>[http://www.associationranucci.org/autour_affaire/revisions.html Affaire Ranucci : POURQUOI R\u00c9VISER ? - Les demandes de r\u00e9visions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303173837/http://www.associationranucci.org/autour_affaire/revisions.html |date=2016-03-03}}.</ref> It was stressed that arguments presented before the [[Ministry of Justice (France)|ministry of Justice]] and the Court of Cassation had already been cited previously by the defence during the criminal trial.<ref>Christian Chardon (September 13, 1978). \"Non ! L'affaire Ranucci n'est pas une erreur judiciaire\", ''[[Minute (newspaper)|Minute]]'' no 857, p. 20.</ref> Despite the creation of the association \"Affaire Ranucci: Pourquoi r\u00e9viser?\" by four Parisian students in 2002, there have been no further attempts to seek reconsideration since 1991 - the rejection date of the last request. Although some rumors circulated in 2006 about the presence of [[serial killer]] [[Michel Fourniret]] in Marseille area in 1974 and his assumed attendance of the Ranucci trial, Fourniret himself rectified saying he went to Marseilles region as a child and was working in Paris when the crime occurred; furthermore, an [[Anthropometry|anthropometric]] study concluded that photographs taken at Ranucci's trial in 1976 of a man who seemed at a first sight to look like Fourniret, did not match pictures of the real Fourniret at that time.<ref>[http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/societe/20060704.OBS3967/fourniret-n-etait-pasau-proces-ranucci.html \"Fourniret n'\u00e9tait pas au proc\u00e8s Ranucci\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727023226/http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/societe/20060704.OBS3967/fourniret-n-etait-pasau-proces-ranucci.html |date=2014-07-27 }}, ''[[Le Nouvel Observateur]]'', July 4, 2006.</ref> On multiple occasions, former President of the Republic Giscard d'Estaing has said in interviews that he did not feel remorse regarding his role in the case; he mentioned to journalist Laurent Delahousse in 2010 that he did not regret his decision to decline clemency to Ranucci, claiming that he was indeed guilty and that \"he had to be punished\".<ref>[http://www.lepoint.fr/politique/giscard-d-estaing-ne-regrette-pas-d-avoir-refuse-sa-grace-a-ranucci-09-10-2010-1247062_20.php \"Giscard d'Estaing ne regrette pas d'avoir refus\u00e9 sa gr\u00e2ce \u00e0 Ranucci\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413090750/http://www.lepoint.fr/politique/giscard-d-estaing-ne-regrette-pas-d-avoir-refuse-sa-grace-a-ranucci-09-10-2010-1247062_20.php |date=2015-04-13 }}, [[Agence France Presse|AFP]] & ''[[Le Point]]'', October 9, 2010.</ref>\n\nH\u00e9lo\u00efse Mathon died on March 14, 2013. She was buried in the graveyard of Saint-V\u00e9ran, Avignon, alongside her son's ashes which she had followed as they were transported from the [[Cimeti\u00e8re Saint-Pierre (Marseille)|graveyard Saint-Pierre]] in Marseille to Saint-V\u00e9ran after his execution.\n\n==Jean-Baptiste Rambla's murder cases==\nIn February 2005 Jean-Baptiste Rambla, Marie-Dolor\u00e8s' brother, was arrested during the investigation into the disappearance of Corinne Beidl, his employer. Rambla had killed her as a result of a violent dispute about his salary. He was convicted of her murder and sentenced  to an 18-year prison term in October 2008. According to his lawyers, his behaviour was influenced by drug addiction and the media coverage surrounding the guilt of his sister's murderer.<ref>[http://www.franceinfo.fr/actu/faits-divers/article/ouverture-du-proces-rambla-sur-fond-d-affaire-ranucci-51781 \"Ouverture du proc\u00e8s Rambla, sur fond d\u2019affaire Ranucci\"], [[France Info]], October 15, 2008.</ref>\n\nAfter being paroled in early 2015, he was charged once more with the brutal murder of a 21-year-old girl committed in [[Toulouse]] in August 2017, and has gone back to jail.<ref>Claire Lagadic (August 12, 2017). [https://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2017/08/12/2627027-le-terrible-passe-de-jean-baptiste-rambla.html \u2033Le terrible pass\u00e9 de Jean-Baptiste Rambla\"] in ''[[La D\u00e9p\u00eache du Midi]]''.</ref> His trial has been postponed after home confinement was imposed in response of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* Bouladou, G\u00e9rard (2005). ''L'affaire du pull-over rouge : Ranucci coupable ! Un pull-over rouge cousu de fil blanc'', Nice: France-Europe \u00c9ditions, 383 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-848-25097-7}})\n* Bouladou, G\u00e9rard (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture. L'affaire Ranucci : toute la v\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur le pull-over rouge'', Aix-en-Provence: Pascal Petiot, 335 p. ({{isbn|978-2-848-14034-6}})\n* Donadini, Genevi\u00e8ve (2016). ''Le proc\u00e8s Ranucci. T\u00e9moignage d'un jur\u00e9 d'assises'', Paris: [[L'Harmattan]], 106 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-343-10540-6}})\n* Fratacci, Mathieu (1994). ''Qui a tu\u00e9 Christian Ranucci ?'', Paris: \u00c9ditions N\u00b0 1, 253 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-863-91605-6}})\n* Le Forsonney, Jean-Fran\u00e7ois (2006). ''Le Fant\u00f4me de Ranucci. Ce jeune condamn\u00e9 qui me hante'', Neuilly-sur-Seine: Michel Lafon, 187 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-749-90561-7}})\n* Osswald, Karin (1994). ''L'affaire Ranucci'', Paris: [[Groupe Flammarion|J'ai lu]], 188 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-277-07077-1}})\n* [[Gilles Perrault|Perrault, Gilles]] (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Paris: Ramsay, 439 p. (republished in [[Le Livre de Poche]] in [[1980 in literature|1980]] & [[Fayard]] in [[1994 in literature|1994]]) ({{ISBN|2-859-56072-6}})\n* Perrault, Gilles (2006). ''L'ombre de Christian Ranucci'', Paris: Fayard, 262 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-213-62887-5}})\n* Perrault, Gilles; Mathon, H\u00e9lo\u00efse; Le Forsonney, Jean-Fran\u00e7ois; Soulez Larivi\u00e8re, Daniel; [[Jean-Denis Bredin|Bredin, Jean-Denis]] (1995). ''Christian Ranucci : vingt ans apr\u00e8s'', Paris: [[\u00c9ditions Julliard|Julliard]], 275 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-260-01091-3}})\n* Rambla, Pierre (2008). ''Le \"Cirque\" Rouge ou Le mensonge m\u00e9diatique et l'argent du sang'', Saint-Denis: Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des \u00c9crivains, 298 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-748-03820-0}})\n* Ranucci, Christian; Mathon, H\u00e9lo\u00efse (1980). ''Jusqu'au 28 juillet 1976 : \u00c9crits d'un condamn\u00e9'', Paris: [[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette Litt\u00e9rature]], 217 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-010-07230-7}})\n* Vincent, Jean-Louis (2018). ''Affaire Ranucci : Du doute \u00e0 la v\u00e9rit\u00e9'', Paris: Fran\u00e7ois Bourin, 460 p. ({{ISBN|979-1-025-20398-9}})}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.justice-affairescriminelles.org/Dossierranucci/Ranucci.html DOSSIER RANUCCI : Peut-on douter ?]\n* [http://www.associationranucci.org/english/english.html Affaire Ranucci : POURQUOI R\u00c9VISER ?]\n* [http://murderpedia.org/male.R/r/ranucci-christian.htm Christian Ranucci | Murderpedia], Juan Ignacio Blanco\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jul/29/archive-guillotine-returns-france-1976 From the archive, 29 July 1976: Guillotine returns after two years], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 29 July 2011\n* {{Find a Grave|114167802}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ranucci, Christian}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Avignon]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:People executed by the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Executed French people]]\n[[Category:People executed by guillotine]]\n[[Category:French murderers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French criminals]]\n[[Category:French murderers of children]]\n[[Category:French people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:People executed by France by decapitation]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Christian Ranucci\n| image_size         =\n| image_name         = \n| image_caption      = \n| birth_name         = Christian Jean Gilbert Ranucci\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1954|4|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Avignon]], [[French Fourth Republic|France]]\n| cause              = Execution by [[guillotine]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1976|7|28|1954|4|6}}\n| death_place        = [[Baumettes prison]], [[Marseilles]], [[French Fifth Republic|France]]\n| resting_place      = Cimeti\u00e8re Saint-V\u00e9ran, Avignon<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/114167802 Christian Jean Ranucci (1954-1976)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110172907/https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/114167802 |date=2016-11-10 }} on [https://www.findagrave.com Find a Grave.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911163501/http://www.findagrave.com/ |date=2016-09-11 }}. Retrieved 10 November 2016.</ref>\n| height             = 5 ft 8 in\n| other_names        = \"Le bourreau du bois de Valdonne\" (\"The torturer of the wood of Valdonne\")<ref>J\u00e9r\u00f4me Ferracci, ''Le M\u00e9ridional'', June 1974; cited by [[Gilles Perrault]] (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 141.</ref>\n| occupation         = [[Door-to-door|Travelling salesman]]\n| conviction = [[Child abduction]] & [[Child murder|murder]] (March 10, 1976)\n| conviction_penalty = [[Capital punishment]] (March 10, 1976)\n| conviction_status  = Executed by guillotine on July 28, 1976\n| parents            = Jean Ranucci and H\u00e9lo\u00efse Mathon\n| victims            = Marie-Dolor\u00e8s Rambla, 8\n| weapons            = [[Rock (geology)|Stones]]<br>[[Switchblade|Flick knife]]\n| states             = [[Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne]]\n| locations          = [[Marseilles]] <small>(abduction)</small> <br/> [[Belcod\u00e8ne]] <small>([[Traffic collision|car accident]])</small> <br>[[Peypin]] <small>([[Crime scene|murder scene]])</small>\n| date               = June 3, 1974\n| apprehended   = June 5, 1974\n}}\n\n'''Christian Ranucci''' (April 6, 1954&nbsp;\u2013 July 28, 1976) was a travelling [[door-to-door]] salesman who abducted and killed an eight-year-old girl on [[Whit Monday]], 1974. For these crimes, he  was one of the last persons [[Capital punishment in France#Executions since 1959|executed in France]]. He was convicted of the abduction and murder on March 10, 1976.\n\nHis case greatly influenced the debate over [[capital punishment in France]] after the book ''Le Pull-over rouge'' (1978) was published by former lawyer and journalist [[Gilles Perrault]]. It called Ranucci's guilt into question, and had a notable impact on public opinion, having sold over one million copies.<ref name=\"50ansfaitsdivers\">[http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x16njet_reportage-50-ans-de-faits-divers-christian-ranucci_webcam ''50 ans de faits divers'', \"Christian Ranucci : la v\u00e9rit\u00e9 impossible\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407051919/http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x16njet_reportage-50-ans-de-faits-divers-christian-ranucci_webcam |date=2015-04-07 }}, [[13\u00e8me Rue (TV channel)|13<sup>e</sup> Rue]], July 13, 2006.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nChristian Ranucci was born in Avignon, France on April 6, 1954, to Jean Ranucci (1921&ndash;1988), a board painter and veteran of the [[First Indochina War|Indochina War]], and H\u00e9lo\u00efse Mathon (1922&ndash;2013), a [[caregiver]].\n\nWhen he was four years old, he witnessed his father slashing his mother in the face with a knife \u2014 similar to the one Ranucci would later use to commit murder<ref name=\"50ansfaitsdivers\" /> \u2014 at the door of a court after their divorce had been pronounced. However, other sources, like Ranucci's father, testified that his son did not really witness this attack, but only saw his injured mother as a [[nursemaid]] was bringing him in her arms back at home.<ref>[[Gilles Perrault]] (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 132.</ref>\n\nMother and son soon fled, moving home numerous times, as H\u00e9lo\u00efse Mathon was afraid that her ex-husband would kill them both (although Jean  never attempted to find his son). As a result of this experience, she became an overprotective mother. Years later, Ranucci, charged with Rambla's murder, confessed to the [[examining magistrate]] that he had lived his entire childhood with the constant fear that his father, depicted as violent by his mother, would eventually find and kill him.<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over-rouge'', Ramsay, p. 195.</ref>\n\nDuring his school years, Ranucci was described as a mediocre pupil, repeating a year, but still earning his [[National diploma (France)|National Diploma]] (BEPC) at the age of 17. He was often violent towards his schoolmates, and remained immature and uncommunicative as a young man.<ref name=\"nationalservicecomrade\">[http://www.justice-affairescriminelles.org/Dossierranucci/ARabineau2.html Dossier Ranucci: entretien avec Alain Rabineau - Dossier Ranucci : Peut-on douter ?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728030251/http://www.justice-affairescriminelles.org/Dossierranucci/ARabineau2.html |date=2014-07-28 }}</ref> Meanwhile, he worked as a waiter at a bar, Le Rio Bravo, owned by his mother, located in [[Saint-Jean-de-Moirans]], near [[Voiron]] ([[Is\u00e8re]]), which he ran when she was absent.<ref name=\"50ansfaitsdivers\" />\n\nThey had lived in [[Nice]] since 1970. Ranucci eventually went to [[Wittlich]], in [[Rhineland-Palatinate]] ([[West Germany]]), in order to complete his [[Military service#France|military service]], which ended in March 1974. According to testimony by several comrades from his army days, his behaviour was impulsive, and his reactions were sometimes disproportionate.<ref name=\"nationalservicecomrade\" /> Later, as the murder case against him was unfolding, he was picked out as the abductor and offender of two children from Nice, but this was not pursued, nor formally proven. On May 24, 1974, he was hired by Ets COTTO, a company that made and sold air-conditioning equipment based in Nice, and began working as a door-to-door salesman.<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 166.</ref>\n\n==The crime==\nWhen his mother refused to accompany him on a [[Pentecost]] weekend trip, Ranucci left Nice alone on June 2, 1974. After visiting the region, he arrived in Marseille on the morning of June 3, 1974. Looking for the home of a former military service comrade, he stopped in the Cit\u00e9 Sainte-Agn\u00e8s housing estate ([[4th arrondissement of Marseille|4th arrondissement]]). Distracted by the sight of a group of children involved in numerous games, he came across Marie-Dolor\u00e8s Rambla, eight years old, and her six-and-a-half year old brother Jean-Baptiste,  along with two nearby children playing behind a building, in the car park of a local garage.<ref>G\u00e9rard Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture. L'affaire Ranucci, toute la v\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur le pull-over rouge'', Pascal Petiot, pp. 157; 216-218.</ref>\n\nWhen the Rambla children were alone, around 11:10{{nbsp}}am - 11:15{{nbsp}}am, he moved his car to the car park, on the same level where  the children were. Telling them he had lost a \"big black dog\", he asked for their help in searching for it. Sending the little boy off to track down the non-existent dog, he stayed with Marie-Dolor\u00e8s, chatting for a few minutes, then persuaded her to get into his car - a grey Peugeot 304. According to his later confession, the girl was initially reluctant to go with him, making him repeat his offer; he eventually gained her trust by promising to return her home for lunch time.\n\nAfter being arrested, he was not recognized by the two witnesses to the abduction, and the only physical evidence implicating him in this phase of the crime was a drawing he made while in police custody showing the estate where the Rambla family lived.<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, pp. 116-121.</ref>\n\nAn hour later, arriving at a crossroads, he went through a stop sign and collided with another car, damaging both vehicles. He then turned around and fled in the direction of Marseilles, drove a few hundred metres before stopping at the bottom of a hill, exited from his car with the young girl, and climbed up into underbrush holding her left arm. Hearing Marie-Dolor\u00e8s screaming and crying (she had just lost her right shoe and had to walk barefoot over the vegetation),<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, p. 27.</ref> he grabbed her by the neck and pushed her temple to the ground. He hit her head with stones then stabbed her in the throat with his [[Switchblade|flick knife]] (she reportedly received about fifteen blows).<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, pp. 23; 110-112.</ref><ref name=\"Rambla_88-92\">Pierre Rambla (2008). ''Le \u2033Cirque\" Rouge ou Le mensonge m\u00e9diatique et l'argent du sang'', Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des \u00c9crivains, pp. 20; 88-92.</ref> Rambla tried to resist by raising her right hand, but Ranucci soon stabbed the dorsal side of her hand.<ref name=\"Rambla_88-92\" /> Afterwards, he covered the body with briars and thornbushes.\n\nReturning to his car, he drove for a while, then hid in a mushroom bed in order to change his flat tire, change his bloodied clothes, clean up, and hide his knife. However, when leaving, he needed help from people to get his car out of the mud. After having accepted a cup of tea, he got back to his home, Corniche Fleurie (overlooking Nice).<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, pp. 33-37.</ref>{{,}}<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, pp. 29-30.</ref>\n\n==Arrest, confession and profile==\nRanucci was arrested two days after the murder as he was returning from his office to his home in Nice. The girl's corpse had been found shortly before by a squad of [[National Gendarmerie|gendarmes]]. He had been identified by his registration plate number, provided by witnesses to the car accident during his flight with the child. He confessed to the abduction and murder of Marie-Dolor\u00e8s Rambla, and drew an accurate sketch of the kidnapping, then indicated the place where he disposed of the murder weapon, his bloodied flick knife, which was later found buried in a peat field stack by gendarmes.\n\nPsychiatrists who heard Ranucci's conversation during sessions diagnosed him as having an \"immature and backward sexuality\". According to their report this, coupled with a need for company, had led to the desire to take children and spend time with them. He was not [[Offender profiling|profiled]] as a  [[Pedophilia|pedophile]], but rather as someone whose sexual identity remained undefined, though the psychiatrists asserted he showed \"keen interest\" in children. While confessing, Ranucci claimed he had no intention of harming the girl and only wished to go for a ride with her.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jul/29/archive-guillotine-returns-france-1976 From the archive, 29 July 1976: \"Guillotine returns after two years\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415011544/https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jul/29/archive-guillotine-returns-france-1976 |date=15 April 2017 }}, [https://www.theguardian.com theguardian.com], July 29, 2011.</ref> He explained the murder was a result of panic and fear due to the accident.\n\nHis motive for the abduction still remains unclear, as no signs of rape or other sexual assault were found on the victim's body.\n\nMonths later, while incarcerated at [[Baumettes prison]] ([[9th arrondissement of Marseille]]), he repudiated his confession after learning he was of the same [[blood type]] as the little girl (bloodstains had been found on his pants seized in his car trunk),<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, p. 322.</ref> and hearing about a local pedophile who wore a red polo shirt or sweater \u2014 according to testimonies \u2014 similar to the one discovered near the mushroom bed where he had hidden after the murder.<ref name=\"Perraultp222-223\">G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 222-223.</ref>\n\nAndr\u00e9 Fraticelli, Ranucci's lawyer, originally planned to plead [[mitigating circumstances]], citing his client's difficult childhood, the sight of his father slashing his mother's face, and the numerous moves made across France as a defence in court. Fraticelli wanted the jury to consider Ranucci's [[wikt:state of mind|state of mind]] and consciousness while committing murder, and whether he was really accountable for the crime, rather than his guilt.{{efn|According to article 64 of the [[French Penal Code of 1810|Penal Code]], no one can be tried if he acted in a state of [[Criminal insanity|insanity]].<ref>[http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichCodeArticle.do?idArticle=LEGIARTI000006490631&cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006071029&dateTexte=19940228 Code p\u00e9nal (ancien) - Article 64] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221090225/https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichCodeArticle.do?idArticle=LEGIARTI000006490631&cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006071029&dateTexte=19940228 |date=2016-12-21 }}. Retrieved 10 December 2016.</ref>}}<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 244-246.</ref> However, as Ranucci had retracted his confession, his other two lawyers conformed to his wishes, and chose to plead his innocence.{{efn|Fraticelli said about the defence strategy: \"You do not play poker with a man's life (...). This is the reason why I thought we had to plead guilty, with mitigating circumstances which were densely represented and possible.\"}}<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, p. 248.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H8HmoRp8QlI?t=48m30s |title=Christian Ranucci : l'\u00e9nigme du pull-over rouge - Faites entrer l'accus\u00e9 #FELA |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= July 17, 2003 |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=[[France 2]] |access-date=30 June 2015 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Trial and execution ==\nHe was tried in [[Aix-en-Provence]] in southern France on March 9 and 10, 1976, just three weeks after [[Patrick Henry (French murderer)|Patrick Henry]] was arrested in [[Troyes]] for another child murder. Journalists described [[public opinion]] as sensitive to the point of hysteria, demanding death penalties for child murderers.\n\nOn the advice of his mother, Ranucci came to [[Cour d'assises|court]] dressed like a clergyman, sporting a large [[pectoral cross]], which irritated most of the jury, and was interpreted by a few observers as an indication of his immaturity. Ranucci appeared arrogant during the trial, denying the crime and his guilt, despite the physical evidence and the details he had provided during his confession.<ref>[http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x79gec_l-affaire-ranucci-l-ombre-d-un-dout_news ''Secrets d'actualit\u00e9'', \"Affaire Ranucci : l'ombre d'un doute\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819084955/http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x79gec_l-affaire-ranucci-l-ombre-d-un-dout_news |date=2014-08-19 }}, [[M6 (TV channel)|M6]], September 4, 2005.</ref>{{,}}<ref>Genevi\u00e8ve Donadini (2016). ''Le proc\u00e8s Ranucci : T\u00e9moignage d'un jur\u00e9 d'assises'', L'Harmattan, p. 52.</ref> Found guilty on all counts on March 10, 1976, he was sentenced to death. During the last hearing, and after his advocate's plea, minutes were communicated at the last moment to the jury and the defence lawyers, which, while not unheard of or illegal, was an extremely rare procedure. This was later used as an argument before the [[Court of Cassation (France)|Court of Cassation]].\n\nAgain on his mother's advice, Ranucci wrote a 74-page document titled \"''R\u00e9capitulatif''\" (\"Summary\") while on [[death row]], in which he summed up the case from his point of view, and attempted to prove he was innocent. G\u00e9rard Bouladou, a retired police officer who has written books about the case, has observed signs of [[Pathological lying|mythomania]] in this document and argued that Ranucci was trying to persuade himself of his own innocence.<ref>G. Bouladou (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture...'', Pascal Petiot, p. 229-230.</ref> His [[Court of  Cassation (France)#Appeals|appeal]] for a second trial was denied by the Court of Cassation on June 17, 1976.<ref>[http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichJuriJudi.do?oldAction=rechJuriJudi&idTexte=JURITEXT000007061353&fastReqId=919750374&fastPos=1/  \"Crim., 17 juin 1976, pourvoi n\u00b0 76-90888 (Rejet du pourvoi en cassation de Christian Ranucci)\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812115901/http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichJuriJudi.do?oldAction=rechJuriJudi&idTexte=JURITEXT000007061353&fastReqId=919750374&fastPos=1%2F |date=2014-08-12 }}.</ref>\n\nOn July 26, President [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]] eventually refused a pardon for Ranucci. He was executed by [[guillotine]] in the courtyard of [[Baumettes prison]], in Marseilles, on July 28, 1976, at 4:13{{nbsp}}am. Two of his lawyers who witnessed the execution claimed his last words were \"R\u00e9habilitez-moi!\" (\"Clear my name!\"), but executioner [[Andr\u00e9 Obrecht]] wrote in his memoirs that the condemned said nothing before dying, his last word being a \"Negative!\" shouted at the chaplain when he refused to receive communion. His third lawyer, Andr\u00e9 Fraticelli, confirmed that Ranucci never asked to be rehabilitated. It is also specified in the minutes of the execution that Ranucci \"made no statement\".<ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1976/07/29/le-proces-verbal-officiel_2951905_1819218.html?xtmc=ranucci&xtcr=149 \"LE PROC\u00c8S-VERBAL OFFICIEL\"], ''[[Le Monde]]'', July 29, 1976.</ref>\n\n== Aftermath: controversy, political debate and attempted requests for review ==\nA novel by [[Gilles Perrault]] entitled ''Le Pull-over rouge'' (''The Red Sweater''), disputed Ranucci's involvement in the crime, expressing the writer's doubts about his guilt. The title of the book refers to a red sweater found hidden in the mushroom bed where Ranucci hid after his car accident, which seemed similar to that worn by another man who [[child sexual abuse|sexually abused]] children in another Marseilles estate, just two days before Rambla's kidnapping and murder.<ref name=\"Perraultp222-223\" /> During the inquiry, when asked about the sweater, Ranucci denied being its owner. In his book, Perrault took on board Ranucci's final defence, arguing that a [[Brain concussion|concussion]] he allegedly suffered as a result of the accident, right at the bottom of the [[crime scene]], caused Ranucci to become victim to manipulation and impersonation by the \"real murderer\". In this theory, the man is supposed to have moved the unconscious door-to-door to the [[Car seat|rear seat]] of Ranucci's own car, then drove the vehicle (carrying Ranucci) to the mushroom bed where he then hid his red sweater.<ref>G. Perrault (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Ramsay, pp. 387-395.</ref> However, nothing within the penal case could corroborate this version; Perrault himself had no explanation or rebuttal to the main evidence, in particular the hiding place of the murder weapon Ranucci revealed.\n\nThe victim's father, Pierre Rambla, vehemently opposed the book and the subsequent campaign that supported Perrault's theses, arguing it made his family suffer, especially his elder son Jean-Baptiste who is among the last people to have seen Marie-Dolor\u00e8s alive.<ref>P. Rambla (2008). ''Le \"Cirque\" Rouge'', Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des \u00c9crivains, pp. 26-29; 56-65.</ref>\n\nThe book was made into a film by [[Michel Drach]] in 1979, starring [[Serge Av\u00e9dikian]] as Ranucci.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/film/le-pull-over-rouge |title=Le Pull-Over Rouge |publisher=Time Out Digital Limited |accessdate=5 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915124210/http://www.timeout.com/london/film/le-pull-over-rouge |archivedate=15 September 2016 }}</ref> A television film about the case, ''L'affaire Christian Ranucci: Le combat d'une m\u00e8re'', starring Alexandre Hamidi and [[Catherine Frot]] as Christian Ranucci and his mother, was broadcast in 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lemonde.fr/vous/article/2010/01/16/l-affaire-ranucci-le-combat-d-une-mere_1292538_3238.html | title=L'affaire Christian Ranucci: Le combat d'une m\u00e8re | publisher=Le Monde.fr | date=January 16, 2010 | accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref>{{,}}<ref>{{cite Web|url=http://www.tf1international.com/int_fiche.php?Film=295 |title=A Mother's Combat - TF1 International |publisher=TF1 International.com |accessdate=2 April 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402082452/http://www.tf1international.com/int_fiche.php?Film=295 |archivedate=2 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe controversy next entered politics, influencing the [[Capital punishment in France#Abolition|debate on capital punishment in France]], which culminated in criminal lawyer, and newly nominated Minister of Justice, [[Robert Badinter]] addressing the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] in September 1981 to defend his bill to abolish capital punishment. As a request for reconsideration had been submitted to him, he claimed, with regard to the Ranucci case, that there were: \"too many questions about his case, and [that] these questions were sufficient [...] to condemn the death penalty\".<ref>[http://blog.bnf.fr/gallica/index.php/2013/04/29/discours-sur-labolition-de-la-peine-de-mort-mise-en-ligne-du-manuscrit-de-robert-badinter/ Discours de Robert Badinter sur l'abolition de la peine de mort] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812085152/http://blog.bnf.fr/gallica/index.php/2013/04/29/discours-sur-labolition-de-la-peine-de-mort-mise-en-ligne-du-manuscrit-de-robert-badinter/ |date=2014-08-12 }}, [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France#Digital library|Gallica]], September 17, 1981.</ref> On the other hand, some journalists who covered the case refuted Perrault's [[miscarriage of justice]] theory. Christian Chardon, who covered the case for ''[[Le Nouveau D\u00e9tective|D\u00e9tective]]'', wrote an article for the newspaper ''[[Minute (French newspaper)|Minute]]'' titled \"Non ! L'affaire Ranucci n'est pas une erreur judiciaire\" (\"No! The Ranucci case was not a miscarriage of justice\") in late 1978, in which he recapped the key points of the case and argued for Ranucci's guilt. Chardon denied that Ranucci had been tortured as claimed during his trial. (In particular, he had accused Commissioner G\u00e9rard Alessandra, chief of the criminal section \"Nord\" in the H\u00f4tel de Police de Marseille, who was in charge of the inquiry.)<ref>Christian Chardon (September 13, 1978). \"Non ! L'affaire Ranucci n'est pas une erreur judiciaire\", ''[[Minute (French newspaper)|Minute]]'' no 857, p. 27.</ref> In late 1979, Jean Laborde published an article in ''[[Paris-Match]]'' which he titled \"Ranucci innocent ? Eh bien non !\" (\"Ranucci innocent? Well no!\"), also refuting Perrault's theory of Ranucci's innocence.\n\nIn 1989, having accused the policemen in charge of the inquiry of \"abuse of authority\" in a 1985 TV program titled ''Qui a tu\u00e9 Christian Ranucci?'' (''Who killed Christian Ranucci?''), Gilles Perrault, as well as the presenter, was found guilty of defamation and fined 30,000 francs to be paid to each of the five policemen, a sentence confirmed and raised on appeals and ''cassation'' to 70,000 francs for each plaintiff.<ref>[https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichJuriJudi.do?idTexte=JURITEXT000007623311 Cour de cassation, Chambre criminelle, du 4 f\u00e9vrier 1992, 90-86.069, In\u00e9dit].</ref>{{,}}<ref name=\"50ansfaitsdivers\" /> In 2008, Perrault and his publisher [[Fayard]] were found guilty of defamation against the Marseille police in another book, ''L'ombre de Christian Ranucci'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fayard.fr/lombre-de-christian-ranucci-9782213628875 |title=L'ombre de Christian Ranucci |publisher=[[Fayard|\u00c9ditions Fayard]] |accessdate=5 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105210208/http://www.fayard.fr/lombre-de-christian-ranucci-9782213628875 |archivedate=5 January 2016 }}</ref> in which it was stated that the investigators behaved with \"casualness and partisanship\". Perrault was fined 5,000 [[euro]]s and his publisher an equal sum for each policeman defamed, a decision confirmed and increased to 10,000 euro for each of the four policemen on appeal in 2009.<ref>[http://www.laprovence.com/actu/gilles-perrault-et-son-editeur-condamnes-pour-diffamation \"Gilles Perrault et son \u00e9diteur condamn\u00e9s pour diffamation\"], ''[[La Provence]]'', January 27, 2009.</ref>\n\nSince the publishing of ''Le Pull-over rouge'', which was followed by the creation of the \"Comit\u00e9 national pour la r\u00e9vision du proc\u00e8s Ranucci\", there have been three requests for a review of the Ranucci trial, all being ultimately rejected, the Minister of Justice and afterwards the \"Commission de r\u00e9vision des condamnations p\u00e9nales\" of the Court of cassation arguing each time that no new facts had proven Ranucci's innocence nor even cast doubt upon his guilt.<ref>[[Associated Press]] (November 30, 1991). [https://www.lesoir.be/art/m/le-pull-over-rouge-pas-de-revision-du-proces-ranucci_t-19911130-Z04PPH.html \"'Le pull-over rouge': pas de r\u00e9vision du proc\u00e8s Ranucci\"], ''[[Le Soir]]''</ref>{{,}}<ref>[http://www.associationranucci.org/autour_affaire/revisions.html Affaire Ranucci : POURQUOI R\u00c9VISER ? - Les demandes de r\u00e9visions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303173837/http://www.associationranucci.org/autour_affaire/revisions.html |date=2016-03-03}}.</ref> It was stressed that arguments presented before the [[Ministry of Justice (France)|ministry of Justice]] and the Court of Cassation had already been cited previously by the defence during the criminal trial.<ref>Christian Chardon (September 13, 1978). \"Non ! L'affaire Ranucci n'est pas une erreur judiciaire\", ''[[Minute (newspaper)|Minute]]'' no 857, p. 20.</ref> Despite the creation of the association \"Affaire Ranucci: Pourquoi r\u00e9viser?\" by four Parisian students in 2002, there have been no further attempts to seek reconsideration since 1991 - the rejection date of the last request. Although some rumors circulated in 2006 about the presence of [[serial killer]] [[Michel Fourniret]] in Marseille area in 1974 and his assumed attendance of the Ranucci trial, Fourniret himself rectified saying he went to Marseilles region as a child and was working in Paris when the crime occurred; furthermore, an [[Anthropometry|anthropometric]] study concluded that photographs taken at Ranucci's trial in 1976 of a man who seemed at a first sight to look like Fourniret, did not match pictures of the real Fourniret at that time.<ref>[http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/societe/20060704.OBS3967/fourniret-n-etait-pasau-proces-ranucci.html \"Fourniret n'\u00e9tait pas au proc\u00e8s Ranucci\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727023226/http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/societe/20060704.OBS3967/fourniret-n-etait-pasau-proces-ranucci.html |date=2014-07-27 }}, ''[[Le Nouvel Observateur]]'', July 4, 2006.</ref> On multiple occasions, former President of the Republic Giscard d'Estaing has said in interviews that he did not feel remorse regarding his role in the case; he mentioned to journalist Laurent Delahousse in 2010 that he did not regret his decision to decline clemency to Ranucci, claiming that he was indeed guilty and that \"he had to be punished\".<ref>[http://www.lepoint.fr/politique/giscard-d-estaing-ne-regrette-pas-d-avoir-refuse-sa-grace-a-ranucci-09-10-2010-1247062_20.php \"Giscard d'Estaing ne regrette pas d'avoir refus\u00e9 sa gr\u00e2ce \u00e0 Ranucci\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413090750/http://www.lepoint.fr/politique/giscard-d-estaing-ne-regrette-pas-d-avoir-refuse-sa-grace-a-ranucci-09-10-2010-1247062_20.php |date=2015-04-13 }}, [[Agence France Presse|AFP]] & ''[[Le Point]]'', October 9, 2010.</ref>\n\nH\u00e9lo\u00efse Mathon died on March 14, 2013. She was buried in the graveyard of Saint-V\u00e9ran, Avignon, alongside her son's ashes which she had followed as they were transported from the [[Cimeti\u00e8re Saint-Pierre (Marseille)|graveyard Saint-Pierre]] in Marseille to Saint-V\u00e9ran after his execution.\n\n==Jean-Baptiste Rambla's murder cases==\nIn February 2005 Jean-Baptiste Rambla, Marie-Dolor\u00e8s' brother, was arrested during the investigation into the disappearance of Corinne Beidl, his employer. Rambla had killed her as a result of a violent dispute about his salary. He was convicted of her murder and sentenced  to an 18-year prison term in October 2008. According to his lawyers, his behaviour was influenced by drug addiction and the media coverage surrounding the guilt of his sister's murderer.<ref>[http://www.franceinfo.fr/actu/faits-divers/article/ouverture-du-proces-rambla-sur-fond-d-affaire-ranucci-51781 \"Ouverture du proc\u00e8s Rambla, sur fond d\u2019affaire Ranucci\"], [[France Info]], October 15, 2008.</ref>\n\nAfter being paroled in early 2015, he was charged once more with the brutal murder of a 21-year-old girl committed in [[Toulouse]] in August 2017, and has gone back to jail.<ref>Claire Lagadic (August 12, 2017). [https://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2017/08/12/2627027-le-terrible-passe-de-jean-baptiste-rambla.html \u2033Le terrible pass\u00e9 de Jean-Baptiste Rambla\"] in ''[[La D\u00e9p\u00eache du Midi]]''.</ref> His trial has been postponned after the end of home confinement imposed in response of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* Bouladou, G\u00e9rard (2005). ''L'affaire du pull-over rouge : Ranucci coupable ! Un pull-over rouge cousu de fil blanc'', Nice: France-Europe \u00c9ditions, 383 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-848-25097-7}})\n* Bouladou, G\u00e9rard (2006). ''Autopsie d'une imposture. L'affaire Ranucci : toute la v\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur le pull-over rouge'', Aix-en-Provence: Pascal Petiot, 335 p. ({{isbn|978-2-848-14034-6}})\n* Donadini, Genevi\u00e8ve (2016). ''Le proc\u00e8s Ranucci. T\u00e9moignage d'un jur\u00e9 d'assises'', Paris: [[L'Harmattan]], 106 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-343-10540-6}})\n* Fratacci, Mathieu (1994). ''Qui a tu\u00e9 Christian Ranucci ?'', Paris: \u00c9ditions N\u00b0 1, 253 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-863-91605-6}})\n* Le Forsonney, Jean-Fran\u00e7ois (2006). ''Le Fant\u00f4me de Ranucci. Ce jeune condamn\u00e9 qui me hante'', Neuilly-sur-Seine: Michel Lafon, 187 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-749-90561-7}})\n* Osswald, Karin (1994). ''L'affaire Ranucci'', Paris: [[Groupe Flammarion|J'ai lu]], 188 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-277-07077-1}})\n* [[Gilles Perrault|Perrault, Gilles]] (1978). ''Le Pull-over rouge'', Paris: Ramsay, 439 p. (republished in [[Le Livre de Poche]] in [[1980 in literature|1980]] & [[Fayard]] in [[1994 in literature|1994]]) ({{ISBN|2-859-56072-6}})\n* Perrault, Gilles (2006). ''L'ombre de Christian Ranucci'', Paris: Fayard, 262 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-213-62887-5}})\n* Perrault, Gilles; Mathon, H\u00e9lo\u00efse; Le Forsonney, Jean-Fran\u00e7ois; Soulez Larivi\u00e8re, Daniel; [[Jean-Denis Bredin|Bredin, Jean-Denis]] (1995). ''Christian Ranucci : vingt ans apr\u00e8s'', Paris: [[\u00c9ditions Julliard|Julliard]], 275 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-260-01091-3}})\n* Rambla, Pierre (2008). ''Le \"Cirque\" Rouge ou Le mensonge m\u00e9diatique et l'argent du sang'', Saint-Denis: Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des \u00c9crivains, 298 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-748-03820-0}})\n* Ranucci, Christian; Mathon, H\u00e9lo\u00efse (1980). ''Jusqu'au 28 juillet 1976 : \u00c9crits d'un condamn\u00e9'', Paris: [[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette Litt\u00e9rature]], 217 p. ({{ISBN|978-2-010-07230-7}})\n* Vincent, Jean-Louis (2018). ''Affaire Ranucci : Du doute \u00e0 la v\u00e9rit\u00e9'', Paris: Fran\u00e7ois Bourin, 460 p. ({{ISBN|979-1-025-20398-9}})}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.justice-affairescriminelles.org/Dossierranucci/Ranucci.html DOSSIER RANUCCI : Peut-on douter ?]\n* [http://www.associationranucci.org/english/english.html Affaire Ranucci : POURQUOI R\u00c9VISER ?]\n* [http://murderpedia.org/male.R/r/ranucci-christian.htm Christian Ranucci | Murderpedia], Juan Ignacio Blanco\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jul/29/archive-guillotine-returns-france-1976 From the archive, 29 July 1976: Guillotine returns after two years], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 29 July 2011\n* {{Find a Grave|114167802}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ranucci, Christian}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Avignon]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:People executed by the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Executed French people]]\n[[Category:People executed by guillotine]]\n[[Category:French murderers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French criminals]]\n[[Category:French murderers of children]]\n[[Category:French people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:People executed by France by decapitation]]\n", "name_user": "F\u00e9lixFR", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJean-Baptiste Rambla's murder cases", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Ranucci"}
